Converting labels to categorical¶

In [63]:
from keras.utils.np_utils import to_categorical
y_train = to_categorical(y_train,num_classes=None)
y_test = to_categorical(y_test,num_classes=None)
y_val = to_categorical(y_val, num_classes=None)

Training neural network¶

In [97]:
def create_model():
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=1024, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(256, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='relu'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(128, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='relu'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='relu'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='relu'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(10,activation='softmax'))
    model.summary()
    return model

Using adam optimizer¶

In [98]:
model = create_model()
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_val,y_val), epochs=200, batch_size=100,  verbose=1, validation_split=0.2)

Observations:

  • We do not see any improvement in the validation loss over each epoch.
  • We will try to tweak the learning rate of the adam optimizer and see the results.
  • We will also use he_normal as the weight initializer.
  • This initailizer draws samples from a truncated normal distribution centered on 0 with stddev = sqrt(2 / fan_in) where fan_in is the number of input units in the weight tensor.

    • Adam with lr = 0.001 and weight intializers as he_normal¶

    In [106]:
    import tensorflow as tf
opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(
    learning_rate=0.0001, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999, epsilon=1e-07, amsgrad=False,
    name='Adam')
    In [107]:
    initializer = tf.keras.initializers.he_normal()
    In [108]:
    model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(256, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))

model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(10,activation='softmax'))

    Observations:

  • Earlier we used 'normal' weight initializer but we did not see much imporvement but after we used he_normal initalizers there was a significant improvement in the cross val accuracy.
  • The f1 and recall score on test data is 0.81
  • This shows that along with learning rate weight initializers are also important when it comes to improving the accuracy of the model.

    • Using dropout layers with dropout rate = 0.25 with adam optimizer¶

    In [122]:
    opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(
    learning_rate=0.0001, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999, epsilon=1e-07, amsgrad=False,
    name='Adam')
    In [123]:
    model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=1024, kernel_initializer=initializer, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
model.add(Dense(256, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
model.add(Dense(128, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer=initializer,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
model.add(Dense(10,activation='softmax'))
model.summary()

    By adding droput layers our model accuracy has detoriated a bit and learning is slow¶

    Using glorot normal as the initializer and adam optimizer with learning rate = 0.0001¶

  • This initializer draws samples from a truncated normal distribution centered on 0 with stddev = sqrt(2 / (fan_in + fan_out)) where fan_in is the number of input units in the weight tensor and fan_out is the number of output units in the weight tensor.

    • In [131]:
    glorot_normal = tf.keras.initializers.glorot_normal
    In [132]:
    model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=1024, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(256, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(128, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(10,activation='softmax'))
model.summary()

    Even with glorot uniform initializer we are getting same recall and f1 score that we got in case of he_normal initializer¶

    Let us try stochastic gradient descent with nestrov momentum¶

  • Usually sgd optimizer converges to the optimal solution slowly.Nestrov momentum will help to converge faster.

  • lr value will be 0.001

  • Weight initializer could be either glorot normal or he_normal

    • In [234]:
    from tensorflow import keras
sgd = keras.optimizers.SGD(lr=0.0001, momentum=0.8, nesterov=True)
    In [235]:
    model_s = Sequential()

    As exepected the convergence without momentum is very slow. Let us try ADAM optimizer with batch normalization¶

    In [155]:
    from tensorflow.keras.layers import BatchNormalization
    In [156]:
    model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=1024, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal, activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dense(256, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dense(128, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(Dense(10,activation='softmax'))
model.summary()

    model1 = Sequential()

model1.add(BatchNormalization())

model1.add(BatchNormalization())
model1.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer=glorot_normal,activation='relu'))
model1.add(BatchNormalization())

    Final Conclusion:

  • Overall the model trained with adam optimizer performs better than sgd.
  • SGD with momentum and batch normalization layers can touch or surpass the performance of adam optimizer.Also convergence is slow when we optimise with sgd without momentum
  • Our models performed better when either he_normal or glorot_normal were used as weight initializers.
  • Introducing dropout layers while training did not help in improving the performance of the model rather it seemed to have detoriated the performance overall.
  • We picked the adam optimized model with batch normalisation and predicted random images correctly as shown above.
